objectives.en:
This course aims
*	to give students in-depth knowledge about the history of folklore studies, its main concepts and contemporary theoretical approaches;
*	to explain the workings of different folklore genres (including myth, legend and place lore) in the everyday culture, communication and identity processes of both individuals and groups;
*	to enhance students' ability to understand the specifics of cultural heritage, and application opportunities in different sectors of society, and to critically assess heritage making and other processes pertaining to cultural heritage;
*	to improve students' skills in reflecting on their professional activities and those of others.

learning_outcomes.en:
Upon successful completion of this course, students should:
*	conceive of folklore as a tradition-based communicative practice and have developed an in-depth understanding of its differences from (intangible) cultural heritage; 
*	have a good command of the concept of genre in folkloristics;
*	be capable of recognising opportunities for using vernacular expressions in community work, identity policy, cultural industry and tourism;
*	be prepared to act as mediators between different actors in the fields of cultural heritage, including communities, entrepreneurs and officials; 
*	have improved their skills in assessing their own professional activities and those of others, in working in teams and in expressing their professional views to different interests groups orally and in writing.
